    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that parking lot idea sounds okay, but what if they keep pushing even after i tell them it's in the parking lot? like they act like these tiny things aren't a big deal and just keep sneaking them in. how do i make them see the actual impact on the sprint?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Dealing with stakeholders who won't take no for an answer can be frustrating, especially when they're not seeing the big picture. One way to make them understand the impact is to use data to illustrate the consequences of scope creep. You can create a \"Scope Creep Impact Map\" that shows how each additional request affects the project's velocity, timeline, and overall cost.\n\nFor example, you can use a simple spreadsheet to track the number of requests, the estimated impact on velocity, and the resulting cost. This can help stakeholders visualize how their requests are affecting the project's trajectory. Just be sure to communicate the results clearly and avoid getting bogged down in technical details.\n\nAnother approach is to use a \"Goblin Meter\" – a simple, visual representation of the scope creep. Each time a stakeholder requests a change, you add a small goblin figurine to a jar or a chart. As the number of goblins grows, it becomes harder to ignore the impact of scope creep. This can be a lighthearted way to make the issue more relatable and memorable.\n\nLastly, consider involving your stakeholders in a \"Scope Creep Simulation\" exercise, where you walk them through the consequences of their requests. This can help",
      "source": "target",
